rth, Cheshire, Anglie"},"da":{"abt 1330–1365":"omkring 1330–1365","1330–1365":"1330–1365","1330–1366":"1330–1366","1363–1417":"1363–1417","1305–1352":"1305–1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1305":"1305","1314":"1314","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1352":"1352","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","abt 1330":"omkring 1330","1417":"1417","Poynton, Cheshire, England":"Poynton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Worth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England":"Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England"},"nl":{"abt 1330–1365":"circa 1330–1365","1330–1365":"1330–1365","1330–1366":"1330–1366","1363–1417":"1363–1417","1305–1352":"1305–1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1305":"1305","1314":"1314","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1352":"1352","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","abt 1330":"circa 1330","1417":"1417","Poynton, Cheshire, England":"Poynton, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Worth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worth, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England":"Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England"},"en":{"abt 1330–1365":"about 1330–1365","1330–1365":"1330–1365","1330–1366":"1330–1366","1363–1417":"1363–1417","1305–1352":"1305–1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1305":"1305","1314":"1314","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1352":"1352","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","abt 1330":"about 1330","1417":"1417","Poynton, Cheshire, England":"Poynton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Worth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England":"Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Worth","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Worth, for example in Cheshire, Dorset, Sussex, and Kent, from Old English <i>worth</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’. The vocabulary word probably survived into the Middle English period in the sense of a subsidiary settlement dependent on a main village, and in some cases the surname may be a topographic name derived from this use. Compare   Worthy  .","North German: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>wort</i> ‘enclosure, elevated piece of land, farmstead’, or a habitational name from a place so named in northern Germany."],"variants":[{"name":"Word","meanings":["Perhaps an Americanized form of Dutch <b>Van der Woord</b>, a habitational name from any of the places called Woord or Woerd.","English: variant of   Worth  ."]},{"name":"Wortmann","meanings":["North German: topographic name for someone who lived on a raised, secure site, Middle Low German <i>wort</i> + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Worth   2."]},{"name":"Worthy","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>worthi</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>worthig</i>, <i>weorthig</i>, <i>wurthig</i>). The surname is probably habitational, from a place so named, such as Worthy (Hampshire, Devon) and Worthy Hill Farm (Wiltshire)."]},{"name":"Wurdeman","meanings":["Americanized form of North German <b>Wurdemann</b>, also <b>Würdemann</b>: topographic name from Middle Low German <i>wurt</i> ‘farm area, field, woodland’. Compare   Worth  .","Americanized form of German <b>Würdemann</b>: from an ancient Germanic personal name formed with Old High German <i>wirdi</i> ‘dignity’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Wirth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Gunter, Dieter, Ernst, Gerhard, Manfred, Reinhold, Armin, Erna.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): occupational name for an inn-keeper, Middle High German <i>wirt</i>, German <i>Wirt</i>.","German: status name for a man who was head of a family and master of his own household, from the same word in the sense ‘provider’."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matilda de Worth was born about 1330, in Poynton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas de Worth, was 26 and her mother, Katherine, was 17. She had at least 1 daughter with William de Hulme. She died in 1365, at the age of 36."},"et":{"abt 1330–1365":"umbes 1330–1365","1330–1365":"1330–1365","1330–1366":"1330–1366","1363–1417":"1363–1417","1305–1352":"1305–1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1305":"1305","1314":"1314","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1352":"1352","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","abt 1330":"umbes 1330","1417":"1417","Poynton, Cheshire, England":"Poynton, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Worth, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Worth, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England":"Poynton with Worth, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"abt 1330–1365":"noin 1330–1365","1330–1365":"1330–1365","1330–1366":"1330–1366","1363–1417":"1363–1417","1305–1352":"1305–1352","1314–1352":"1314–1352","1305":"1305","1314":"1314","1366":"1366","1365":"1365","1352":"1352","1363":"1363","1330":"1330","abt 1330":"noin 1330","1417":"1417","Poynton, Cheshire, England":"Poynt